{
  "intro": {
    "title": "Prepositions: Dependent",
    "sections": [
      {
        "title": "What are dependent prepositions?",
        "content": "**Dependent prepositions** are fixed prepositions that belong to a particular verb, noun or adjective.\n- You cannot change them without sounding wrong.",
        "diagrams": [
          {
            "type": "examples",
            "items": [
              {
                "good": "interested **in**",
                "bad": "interested on / interested at",
                "why": "the preposition is fixed"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "root_ids": [
          "B2.collocations.dependent_prepositions"
        ],
        "cefr_level": "B2"
      },
      {
        "title": "Examples",
        "content": "Changing the preposition usually makes the sentence wrong.",
        "diagrams": [
          {
            "type": "examples",
            "items": [
              {
                "good": "I'm interested **in** history."
              },
              {
                "good": "It depends **on** the weather."
              },
              {
                "good": "She's good **at** maths."
              },
              {
                "good": "We complained **about** the noise."
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "root_ids": [
          "B2.collocations.dependent_prepositions"
        ],
        "cefr_level": "B2"
      },
      {
        "title": "Why they matter",
        "content": "Dependent prepositions are very common in exams — especially gap-fill and open cloze.",
        "diagrams": [
          {
            "type": "callout",
            "text": "There is no single rule — you have to learn each pair as a **chunk** (e.g. depend **on**, interested **in**)."
          }
        ],
        "root_ids": [
          "B2.collocations.dependent_prepositions"
        ],
        "cefr_level": "B2"
      },
      {
        "title": "Verb / noun / adjective + preposition",
        "content": "Common examples, grouped by the word the preposition belongs to.",
        "diagrams": [
          {
            "type": "chips",
            "title": "Common chunks",
            "groups": [
              {
                "label": "verb +",
                "items": [
                  "depend on",
                  "listen to",
                  "wait for",
                  "apply for",
                  "complain about",
                  "suffer from"
                ]
              },
              {
                "label": "noun +",
                "items": [
                  "reason for",
                  "solution to",
                  "answer to",
                  "increase in",
                  "interest in",
                  "relationship with"
                ]
              },
              {
                "label": "adjective +",
                "items": [
                  "interested in",
                  "good at",
                  "afraid of",
                  "proud of",
                  "tired of",
                  "responsible for",
                  "worried about"
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "root_ids": [
          "B2.collocations.dependent_prepositions"
        ],
        "cefr_level": "B2"
      },
      {
        "title": "Useful pattern",
        "content": "Often the noun follows the same preposition as the verb/adjective.",
        "diagrams": [
          {
            "type": "formula",
            "items": [
              {
                "label": "adjective → noun",
                "formula": "interested **in** → interest **in**"
              },
              {
                "label": "verb → noun",
                "formula": "complain **about** → complaint **about**"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "root_ids": [
          "B2.collocations.dependent_prepositions"
        ],
        "cefr_level": "B2"
      },
      {
        "title": "How to learn them",
        "content": "There is no single rule — you have to learn each combination as a **chunk**. Try these strategies:\n- Write the preposition together with the word: *depend **on***, not just *depend*.\n- When you meet a new one, add it to a list under Verb / Noun / Adjective.\n- Full reference lists are in the **Dependent Prepositions** section under Reference.",
        "root_ids": [
          "B2.collocations.dependent_prepositions"
        ],
        "cefr_level": "B2"
      }
    ]
  },
  "check": {
    "title": "Test your understanding",
    "root_ids": [
      "B2.collocations.dependent_prepositions"
    ],
    "cefr_level": "B2",
    "questions": [
      {
        "type": "mc",
        "question": "Which sentence is correct?",
        "options": {
          "a": "I'm interested in history.",
          "b": "I'm interested on history.",
          "c": "I'm interested about history.",
          "d": "I'm interested for history."
        },
        "correct_option": "a",
        "explanation": "Dependent preposition (adjective): interested **in** something."
      },
      {
        "type": "mc",
        "question": "Which preposition completes the phrase? 'It depends ____ the weather.'",
        "options": {
          "a": "of",
          "b": "from",
          "c": "on",
          "d": "about"
        },
        "correct_option": "c",
        "explanation": "Dependent preposition (verb): depend **on** something."
      },
      {
        "type": "mc",
        "question": "Choose the correct noun + preposition pair.",
        "options": {
          "a": "a solution for the problem",
          "b": "a solution at the problem",
          "c": "a solution on the problem",
          "d": "a solution to the problem"
        },
        "correct_option": "d",
        "explanation": "Dependent preposition (noun): solution **to** a problem."
      },
      {
        "type": "mc",
        "question": "Which preposition completes the phrase? 'She's afraid ____ spiders.'",
        "options": {
          "a": "for",
          "b": "from",
          "c": "of",
          "d": "at"
        },
        "correct_option": "c",
        "explanation": "Dependent preposition (adjective): afraid **of** something."
      },
      {
        "type": "mc",
        "question": "Which option completes the sentence? 'They complained ____ the noise.'",
        "options": {
          "a": "about",
          "b": "on",
          "c": "for",
          "d": "of"
        },
        "correct_option": "a",
        "explanation": "Dependent preposition (verb): complain **about** something."
      }
    ]
  },
